{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517031"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:50:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:50:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12753"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12753"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.04,0.77,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75727"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5200"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61245"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7861"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25848"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42807"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75727"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presented to a rural hospital with sudden onset severe, crushing chest pain, radiating to his left arm for 1 hour. On examination, he was diaphoretic and tachycardic with a pulse of 140/min, respiratory rate of 26/min, and blood pressure was 90/60 mmHg. His ECG showed ST-segment elevation in leads II, III, aVF, and V4-V6. Cardiac troponin levels were 900ng/mL. The patient was diagnosed with an acute ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI), and fibrinolytic therapy was initiated immediately because the hospital was not PCI capable. After 60 minutes, the patient had very minor relief of his symptoms there was a 20% reduction in ST-segment elevation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What should be the next most important step of management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat fibrinolytic therapy","Administer abciximab","Transfer for urgent percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI","Administer intravenous nitroglycerin","Initiate statin therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario has presented with signs and symptoms of an acute ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction and since he presented in a setup that was PCI incapable, so fibrinolytic therapy was started. According to the guideline if a patient shows \u226450% ST recovery at 60\u201390 minutes, and/or with haemodynamic instability,\u003Cstrong\u003E immediate transfer for urgent PCI \u003C/strong\u003Eis recommended. Time is critical in the management of acute STEMI, and delaying revascularisation can lead to worse outcomes. Therefore, transferring the patient to a tertiary care centre capable of performing urgent coronary angiography and PCI is the most appropriate option for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe guidelines recommend against the use of \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat fibrinolytic therapy\u003C/strong\u003E for patients with STEMI. This approach is associated with a higher risk of bleeding, and it does not improve patient outcomes. Therefore, repeating fibrinolytic therapy is not the most appropriate option for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering abciximab\u003C/strong\u003E, a glycoprotein IIb/IIIa inhibitor is often used in conjunction with fibrinolytic therapy or PCI to reduce the incidence of re-infarction and other adverse cardiac events. However, it is not the most appropriate option in this case as the patient requires urgent coronary angiography and PCI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStatin therapy should be initiated for long term management of atherosclerotic coronary artery disease however it is less helpful in this acute setting\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitroglycerin\u003C/strong\u003E is used to relieve chest pain and improve blood flow to the heart. However, it is not the most appropriate option in this case, as the patient requires urgent revascularisation instead of just symptomatic relief.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["For a STEMI patient who has received fibrinolytic therapy and has 20% recovery in ST-segment elevation after 90 minutes, the most important next step is transferring the patient to a PCI-capable hospital for urgent coronary angiography and PCI."],"references":["Chew DP, Scott IA, Cullen L, French JK, Briffa TG, Tideman PA, et al. National Heart Foundation of Australia and Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Australian clinical guidelines for the management of acute coronary syndromes 2016. Medical Journal of Australia. 2016;205(3):128\u201333"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61245"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12753"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61245"},"attributes":{"cre